    [ Edit ][ Reply ]     		Reply [Jeff Song - 2025-12-02 15:43:02]

    Hello Jeff,

    The scope from the customer has broadened a little more, so some clarity on your points:

    1. The customer will be using RSSO to be able to apply UserFW and UTM profiles to subscriber groups. While this does not affect this logging requirement as such, it does mean that the Framed IP/Framed-IPv6 will get recorded in the traffic log anyway as "srcip" so we can remove these. But we need to support at least two potential Class(25) attributes as RSSO can support up to two. So the number of attributes we are capturing is reduced to 9 as follows

    --Calling-Station-ID(31), 3GPP-IMSI(1), Called-Station-ID(30), 3GPP-Session-S-NSSAI(125), 3GPP-IMEISV(20), 3GPP-RAT-Type(21), 3GPP-User-Location-Info(22), Class(25)--, Class(25)--

    Where an attribute is not provided, this should simply be skipped. It may be the case that only one Class(25) is used/provided so the RADIUS Acct message only contains one. Or it may contain two.

    Also, attributes that have values which are not easy to read/understand (such as octets type - e.g. User-Location-Info, S-NSSAI and Class) should provide hexdump of the value. This ensures better representation of the variations in potential values that these different attributes may have. You will see my example below which indicates this.

    2. I agree with reducing log length, which also reducing values to 9 will help with. To save the length I propose to use a brief descriptor for each attribute. If we only look at the AVP index then there is a risk of overlap as some of the 3GPP attribute index numbers overlap with default RADIUS values. Also, when the log is recieved on the logging system there would need to be a further mapping mechanism to make the index values more easily understandable.

    Here is an example of how I would expect it in this brief description view:

    3gpp-radius-info:[calling:8829990000001],[imsi:001010000000001],[called:fictional.apn.com],[nssai:de93ad8b],[imeisv:350000000000001],[rat:7],[loc:0000f1105ee71981],[class:47726f75703031],[class:536d617274]

    Note1: in this example I have also included the second Class(25) attribute mentioned in point 1. above and also removed the Framed-IP-Address(8) and Framed-IPv6-Prefix(97)

    Note2: this example is based on the attached PCAP from the original NFR, which I add here to this Top3 for reference also. We are using the first entry in the PCAP to create the example.

    Thanks,
    Tom

    Laura Yang (yangl)

    [ Edit ][ Reply ]     		It is difficult to compose the string in the desired nested format:

    [26:[10415:[1:001010000000001],[125:de93ad8b],[20:350000000000001],[21:7],[22:0000f1105ee71981]]]


    because each 3GPP attribute is encoded as an individual Vendor-Specific Attribute (VSA) in the RADIUS packet. VSAs are delivered as separate, flat attributes, rather than as a single grouped structure.

    They may arrive in any order and are not guaranteed to be contiguous. Therefore, the decoder must process each VSA independently and aggregate them into a single logical container, instead of relying on an already nested representation in the original data.

    My suggestion is as following. This approach is also consistent with how RADIUS VSAs are typically organized, i.e., as a flat list of independent attributes rather than a predefined hierarchical structure.

    [26:[10415:[1:001010000000001]]],[26:[10415:[125:de93ad8b]]],[26:[10415:[20:350000000000001]]],[26:[10415:[21:7]]],[26:[10415:[22:0000f1105ee71981]]]

    [ Edit ][ Reply ]     		Reply [Laura Yang - 2025-12-10 10:05:30]

    After some further discussion, we think we would like to log as follows:

    3gpp-radius-info="0|31=8829990000001,10415|1=001010000000001,0|30=fictional.apn.com,10415|125=de93ad8b,10415|20=350000000000001,10415|21=7,10415|22=0000f1105ee71981,0|25=47726f75703031,0|25=536d617274"

    - Use 0 as the vendor code for standard AVPs
    - Use | separator between vendor code and type
    - Use = separator between type and value

    - Using : is possibly not a safe option in case some values include this (we know of some 5G parameters where this is the case
    - If the value contains a comma, the it should be escaped - it is possible the network vendors could encode multiple sub fields using comma

    i.e. 10415|20=350000000000001\,350000000000002

    [ Edit ][ Reply ]     		Hi Joel,

    Some implementation details are as following for your reference. If any problem please let me know. Thanks

    1. Escape the special characters ",|=\" since they are used in our new format.
    2. The max size of the radius-info string is 512. If the string exceeds 512 after adding an attribute this attribute will be discarded.
    3. The following 3 attributes are formatted as hex string and a prefix "0x" is added. The behavior is similar as that in freeRadius.
            Class = 0x64796e616d69635f70726f66696c655f32
            3GPP-Session-S-NSSAI = 0x6465393361643862
            3GPP-User-Location-Info = 0x0000f1105ee71981

    The string sent to miglog is as following:

    "0|30=AA-BB-CC-DD-EE-FF:MySSID,0|31=Jeff\,Wang,0|25=0x64796e616d69635f70726f66696c655f31,0|25=0x64796e616d69635f70726f66696c655f32,10145|1=310150123456789,10145|125=0x02aa5501,10145|20=350000000000039,10145|21=1005,10145|22=0x050530272000a1"

    Regards,
    Laura

    [ Edit ][ Reply ]     		I tested this on 3800G, and found 4 issues:

    ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Problem1 - RAT Type wrong in the log
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

    The problem is that the RAT-Type is a byte value (1 byte), but the firewall is probably interpreting it as 32-bit integer so it is taking 4 bytes (RAT-type and the next 3 bytes).
    In my test I sent the value 6 for RAT-Type, but the firewall is showing "10145|21=102371328":
    3: date=2026-02-03 time=10:09:41 eventtime=1770109781183352764 tz="+0100" logid="0000000013" type="traffic" subtype="forward" level="notice" vd="root" srcip=10.1.0.2 srcport=31191 srcintf="VLAN-C" srcintfrole="undefined" dstip=10.101.3.2 dstport=443 dstintf="VLAN-S" dstintfrole="undefined" srccountry="Reserved" dstcountry="Reserved" sessionid=268596 proto=6 action="close" policyid=1 policytype="policy" poluuid="53109d0e-db37-51f0-507e-36779fd143df" policyname="Allow-Netflix" user="user1" group="Netflix1" authserver="root" rssoinfo="0|30=gNB351,0|31=user1,10145|1=001012466534078,10145|20=352194754207541,10145|21=102371328,10145|22=0xfc8fb71dee8bdb2a,10145|125=0x35351976,0|25=0x67726f7570303031" service="HTTPS" trandisp="noop" appcat="unscanned" duration=2 sentbyte=2506 rcvdbyte=522383 sentpkt=20 rcvdpkt=400

    This is what is sent:
      Acct-Status-Type: Start (1)
      Called-Station-Id: gNB351

    [ Edit ][ Reply ]     		Hi Igor,

    The class[1] is same. But the class[2] is different. Does the new class[2] match the rsso group in config?

    If the matched groups are not changed(unmatched or match same groups) it means the logons are not changed. So we don't send an update message to kernel.

    If it matches a new group the logon is changed so an update message will be sent to kernel.

    Thanks.
     
    Igor Jukic (ijukic)
    2026-02-11 11:05:48

    [ Edit ][ Reply ]     		Hi Laura,

    No, the Class1 is the group membership, and I suppose it is most of the time expected to remain the same. And that part seems problematic to me, because if auth list is cleared without the radius db, the subsequent radius messages will not refresh (create) the auth list entry.
    Probably the best solution would be to always update the kernel no matter the group value.

    I understand that following the rule to always clear both things (auth list and radius db) will prevent this issue, but I suppose it is realistic that customers do not always do that properly.

    Regards
    Igor

    Jeff Wang (jwang)
    2026-02-11 11:22:12

    [ Edit ][ Reply ]     		hi Igor,
    The RSSO feature setup auth session.
    The order is like:
    FGT receive Radius Account Start-->FGT setup DB->match user group with "class" attritue-->set up auth session ->permit traffic.

    So clear "auth session" will not impact DB.
    When FGT receive Radius Account Stop, it will clear DB ,then clear auth session.
    if "rsso-flush-ip-session enable", it will clear match session.
     
    Igor Jukic (ijukic)
    2026-02-11 12:41:05

    [ Edit ][ Reply ]     		Hi Jeff, Laura,

    Yes, the problem is that if the auth session is cleared manually, the subsequent Start will not re-create it. But I get your point, in real-life scenario, probably most of the time there will be a Stop between 2 Start accounting messages, which should solve the issue, since the Stop would erase the radius db entry, but still I suppose we cannot exclude completely a possibility of a new Start being sent without a Stop message.
    The problem with documenting this is that the auth list can be cleared with the filter, but don't see a way to clear radiusd with some filter applied, without clearing the whole db.

    Regards
    Igor
